    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1535997085,
    "last_edit_date" : 1535997085,
    "creation_date" : 1531698521,
    "answer_id" : 51353058,
    "question_id" : 1945213,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>For me, <kbd>Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>F12</kbd> Works really well!</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 447431,
      "reputation" : 441,
      "user_id" : 841050,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a39bb1ebe4edf860055f86785acef5aa?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Svilen",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/841050/svilen"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1558081945,
    "creation_date" : 1558081945,
    "answer_id" : 56182591,
    "question_id" : 1945213,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>For some <strong>Linux</strong> kinds, and particularly for <strong>XFCE</strong> (like Xubuntu, Mint XFCE) a lot of default XWin keyboard layout <strong>mappings are not working</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>This is because they overlap with assigned <em>Window Manager</em> -> <em>Keyboard</em> shortcuts.\nFor the concrete question <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>F12</kbd> is assigned to <em>Workspace 12</em> which I doubt that many use at all. </p>\n\n<p>The <strong>solution</strong> is to clear those Window manager assignments in <em>Window Manager</em> -> <em>Keyboard</em> tab. As a temporal workaround you may use IDEA actions via <em>Find action</em> <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Shift</kbd>+<kbd>A</kbd></p>\n\n<p>There are other overlapping short keys. References:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/51331998\">Difference between Default and Default XWin keymaps</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://youtrack.jetbrains.com/issue/IDEABKL-7658?\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Avoid shortcut conflicts in Linux keymap</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://intellij-support.jetbrains.com/hc/en-us/community/posts/206840705-File-structure-on-CTRL-F12-dissapeared-in-13-1-5-\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">File structure on CTRL+F12 dissapeared in 13.1.5</a></li>\n</ul>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 4116853,
      "reputation" : 11165,
      "user_id" : 3378204,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 91,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/jrjpD.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Eugene",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3378204/eugene"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1578048442,
    "last_edit_date" : 1578048442,
    "creation_date" : 1577947388,
    "answer_id" : 59559303,
    "question_id" : 1945213,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>As mentioned, I'm using XFCE from windows to remote Ubuntu and <kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>F12</kbd> doesn't work. Since no one mentioned recombine, I'd like to share my solution.   </p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><kbd>Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>Alt</kbd> + <kbd>s</kbd>` to open settings. </li>\n<li>Click <code>Keymap</code></li>\n<li>Input <code>file structure</code> in search box</li>\n<li>Right click the item and click <code>Add Keyboard Shortcut</code></li>\n<li>Press keyboard combination you like and I used Ctrl + <kbd>Shift</kbd> + <kbd>o</kbd> since I came from Eclipse world. The <kbd>Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>o</kbd> has been bound already, so I used <kbd>Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>Shift</kbd> + <kbd>o</kbd> instead</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Now, you can use Ctrl + <kbd>Shift</kbd> + <kbd>o</kbd> to trigger the file structure. </p>\n\n<p>For details about keymap rebinding, please refer to <a href=\"https://www.jetbrains.com/help/idea/configuring-keyboard-and-mouse-shortcuts.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">this thread</a>. </p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1352612,
      "reputation" : 4558,
      "user_id" : 1357094,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 85,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/73b4bd192fc3756a1ad0de1bb534f11c?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "cellepo",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1357094/cellepo"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 4,
    "last_activity_date" : 1597854432,
    "last_edit_date" : 1597854432,
    "creation_date" : 1593993659,
    "answer_id" : 62747580,
    "question_id" : 1945213,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you want a persistent/sticky/docked Tool Window instead of a temporary/transient dialog:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><em>Mac</em>: <kbd>⌘</kbd>+<kbd>7</kbd></li>\n</ul>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 14140946,
      "reputation" : 101,
      "user_id" : 10215782,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/6cdUb6BM.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Sunil",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/10215782/sunil"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1724042194,
    "last_edit_date" : 1724042194,
    "creation_date" : 1723985836,
    "answer_id" : 78884648,
    "question_id" : 1945213,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>As I had windows fn-keyboard (I needed to press ctrl+fn+F12)</p>\n<p>In order to reduce the number of key pressed.</p>\n<p>Could disable (fn) by pressing fn+Esc.</p>\n<p>Finally could use ctrl+F12 for the dialog popup in intelliJ IDE.</p>\n"
  } ],
